<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n12146d"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n12" href="#n12146d">N12 (VI.B.14)</a>:  <a href="../../ff/fnbs/n12all.htm#n12146d"> 146(d)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> ~ builds church 19 ft l.</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">L&apos;oeuvre qui s&apos;imposait avant toute autre &agrave; l&apos;&eacute;v&ecirc;que &eacute;tait la construction de son &eacute;glise; il y travaillait de ses mains, donnant ainsi l&apos;exemple. A un voyage de saint Patrice en Connaught, l&apos;un de ses disciples, l&apos;&eacute;v&ecirc;que Olcan, d&eacute;sirant &eacute;tablir une &eacute;glise pour lui-m&ecirc;me, et ayant obtenu l&apos;autorisation de saint Patrice, partit dans la for&ecirc;t avex sa hache sur les &eacute;paules&agrave;. L&apos;&eacute;glise, un simple rectangle, n&apos;avait jamais plus de soicante pieds de long, quelquefois sa longueur ne d&eacute;passait pas quinze pieds <br><font color="green">[126: The work which was principally enjoined on a bishop was the building of his church; he worked at it with his own hands, thus setting an example. On one of St Patrick&apos;s journeys in Connaught, on of his disciples, the Bishop Olcan, wishing to erect a church for himself, and having obtained St Patrick&apos;s permission, started into the forest with his axe on his shoulders.&hellip; The church, a simple rectangle, was never more than sixty feet long, sometimes not more than fifteen feet]</font> <small> Riguet, Abb&eacute; <a name="RTSP" href="../../ff/fdra/fdex.htm#RTSP"><cite title="source">Saint Patrice</cite></a> (1911) 150</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
